## Environment data

Server 2012 R2 VSTS build agents

ClientWebSocket on .NET Core does not provide the upgrade request errors in the exception details as it does on the .NET Framework.
Repro code
var client = new ClientWebSocket();
client.ConnectAsync(new Uri("wss://speech.platform.bing.com/speech/recognition/interactive/cognitiveservices/v1"), CancellationToken.None).GetAwaiter().GetResult();

ClientWebSocket on .NET Core does not provide the upgrade request errors in the exception details as it does on the .NET Framework.
Repro code
var client = new ClientWebSocket();
client.ConnectAsync(new Uri("wss://speech.platform.bing.com/speech/recognition/interactive/cognitiveservices/v1"), CancellationToken.None).GetAwaiter().GetResult();

Avoid taking a lock to get an available connection when there is a valid connection to be had in the connection pool. On my machine on a microbenchmark that uses HttpClient.GetAsync to make lots of small, concurrent requests to a localhost server, this appears to provide around a 10% throughput win.

@geoffkizer, could you try it out and let me know what you see with your test?

@aviviadi, @ayende, can you please also try it and confirm that it addresses your contention concerns from #31799?

@mikeharder, I believe you had a benchmark where you thought contention was showing up as an issue.  Could you try this with your benchmark as well?

